The paper deals with Byzantine consensus protocols, which are commonly studied in the Distributed Computing (cs.DC) sub-category. The focus on optimizing performance in the common case suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the sub-categories of Cryptography and Security (cs.CR), Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS), and Systems and Control (cs.SY). The use of communication efficiency and information theory principles in the design of the protocol layers suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the Information Theory (cs.IT) sub-category.
